**(2) Moral of the Story:**

The moral is a warning against arrogance born of success. Even when one is successful — especially when one is unmatched in ability — one must remain humble and vigilant. Chu Zhuang Wang’s worry stemmed not from failure, but from the realization that his own greatness might isolate him from the wisdom of others, and that such isolation could lead to downfall. Wu Qi’s lesson is that true leadership requires self-awareness and the humility to recognize that one’s success may be a sign of danger, not triumph.

In essence:  
> **Success without humility is the beginning of ruin.**  
> **A ruler must be wary of the danger of self-satisfaction — even when surrounded by capable ministers, one must never forget the peril of thinking oneself indispensable.**

This is a classic Confucian and Xunzi-style admonition: rulers must cultivate moral self-discipline, recognize their own limitations, and remain open to counsel — even when they are the most capable.

